==English==

===Etymology===
{{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|lynspin}}, compound of {{m|enm|lins||axletree}} and {{m|enm|pin}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|lynis||linchpin}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*luniso}} (compare {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|Lünse}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} (compare {{etyl|cy|-}} {{m|cy|olwyn||wheel}}, {{etyl|xcl|-}} {{m|xcl|ողն||back; spine, backbone}}, {{etyl|sa|-}} {{m|sa|आणि||linchpin|tr=āṇí}}). Figurative use attested from the mid-20th century.

===Alternative forms===
* {{l|en|lynchpin}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# a pin inserted through holes at the end of an [[axle]], so as to secure a wheel
# {{label|en|figuratively}} a central [[cohesive]] source of [[stability]] and [[security]]; a person or thing that is critical to a system or organisation.

